# Operational Runbooks

<!--
This document contains operational runbooks for incident response. Each runbook
is tied to a monitoring rule and/or SLO, providing structured diagnosis and
remediation procedures for known failure modes.

ID convention: RB-001, RB-002, ...
-->

## 1. Runbook Index

| ID | Title | Trigger | Severity | Monitoring Refs | SLO Refs |
|----|-------|---------|----------|----------------|----------|
| RB-001 | <!-- High Error Rate on API --> | <!-- error_rate > 5% --> | <!-- critical --> | <!-- MON-001, MON-002 --> | <!-- SLO-001 --> |

## 2. Runbook Entries

### RB-001 — <!-- title -->

**Trigger Condition**

<!-- e.g. error_rate > 5% for 5 minutes, as detected by MON-001. -->

**Severity**: <!-- critical / warning / info -->

**Symptoms**

- <!-- 5xx responses spike visible in Service Overview dashboard -->
- <!-- PagerDuty alert fires on MON-001 -->
- <!-- increased latency reported by users -->

**Diagnosis Steps**

1. <!-- Check error logs for stack traces:
   `kubectl logs -l app=api --tail=100 | grep ERROR` -->
2. <!-- Verify upstream dependency health:
   `curl -s https://api.example.com/health` -->
3. <!-- Check recent deployments:
   `kubectl rollout history deployment/api` -->

**Remediation Steps**

1. <!-- [manual] Roll back to previous release:
   `kubectl rollout undo deployment/api` -->
2. <!-- [auto] Auto-scaling triggered if replica count < threshold -->
3. <!-- [manual] Verify health checks pass:
   `curl -s https://api.example.com/health` -->

**Escalation Path**

| Level | Contact | Channel | Timeout |
|-------|---------|---------|---------|
| <!-- 1 --> | <!-- on-call engineer --> | <!-- pagerduty --> | <!-- 15m --> |
| <!-- 2 --> | <!-- team lead --> | <!-- phone --> | <!-- 30m --> |
| <!-- 3 --> | <!-- engineering manager --> | <!-- phone + bridge call --> | <!-- 1h --> |

**Rollback Reference**: <!-- PL-001 (see Pipeline Configuration for rollback procedure) -->

